  (text "RAM -> Upper address space, i.e. to 7FFF (word!)\nRAM -> 8k blocks, as per HP design.\nRAM -> 7000-7FFF (8k)\n       6000-7FFF (16k)\n       5000-7FFF (24k)\n       4000-7FFF (32k)\nBit 14 -> SET, 13+12=block..."
    (at 130.81 51.435 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify right bottom))
    (uuid 3f9d83ab-24c8-4fa5-bb30-346ecfee19d1)
  )
  (text "Tested REV-A on a breadboard; Success as of 7-April-2026!"
    (at 154.94 208.28 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid a5e8d4eb-6ac0-438e-8f8b-7937042a18a3)
  )
  (text "Some signals explained:\n\n~{STM}   -> STart Memory. Goes low on memory cycle begin;\n          IDA contains address in question then.\n~{IDAx}   -> Instruction/Data/Address bus.\n~{MEB}   -> Memory busy. Pull low (O.C.) when the memory isn't \n          ready for the requested operation\nRD     -> Read Now. Will be put high to call for the RAM to put\n          data on the bus as negotiated.\n~{WR}     -> Cycle is a memory write operation.\n~{BYTE}   -> low if only a half-word is requested. \n          IDA15 indicates low/high as part of the address!\n          For read this can be ignored, but write would\n          overwrite random data in the wrong chip!\nALE    -> Address Latch Enabled\n~{OE}     -> Enable RAM output\nMEMCLK -> Main system clock to align the memory cycle; \n          STM starts it, one clock later the IDA bus should\n          go from address to data, one way or the other.\n"
    (at 283.845 221.615 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid b7995a3f-ab22-4600-8c2b-3083da659fd7)
  )

